Ali, who unwittingly gets the upper hand in the game, is made to believe by Sang-woo that both can survive the game. He deceives Ali into giving up his marbles. Sadly, Ali's innocence eventually leads to his downfall. #SquidGame #Gganbu

Meanwhile, Ji-yeong and Sae-byeok discuss their lives before playing the marble game. After their poignant interaction, Ji-yeong loses the game on purpose and makes the ultimate sacrifice as she believes Sae-byeok deserves to live more than her. #SquidGame #Gganbu

With Il-nam on the verge of winning, Gi-hun takes advantage of the former's dementia to cheat, even though he feels guilty about it. The scene where Il-nam reveals he was aware of Gi-hun's betrayal but allows him to win anyway—absolutely gut-wrenching. #SquidGame #Gganbu
The set-up of Game 4 reminds Il-nam of his childhood home and is disinterested in playing the marble game, but Gi-hun eventually convinces him to play. #SquidGame #Gganbu
Episode 6, #Gganbu, is one of the finest hours in the history of television. This episode wrecked me and moved me to tears. #SquidGame

Cho Sang-woo is a selfish person who will descend to any depths to survive and win the game. On the other hand, Abdul Ali is a kind-hearted, easily manipulated, but physically powerful immigrant. #SquidGame

Kang Sae-byeok is the most enigmatic character among the main characters. She begins to open up during the latter half of the season after she is paired with another girl with a tragic past, Ji-yeong, who helps her open up. #SquidGame
Oh Il-nam, as Player 001, is delightful. During the initial few episodes, he was my favourite character, and I wished to have his zest for life despite suffering from a terminal ailment. #SquidGame
During the course of the series, Seong Gi-hun, a gambling addict in serious debt, tries hard to be honest and self-righteous in a place of continuous moral decadence. #SquidGame

The commentary on the class divide and the perils of capitalism are apparent throughout the series.  After the horrors of Red Light, Green Light, the participants unanimously quit. Not only they're compelled to return but are made to believe they did it voluntarily. #SquidGame

A group of desperate individuals, in dire financial straits, are manipulated into participating in children's games with a cash prize of roughly $40M. But, they leave out one tiny detail—the games have deadly consequences. #SquidGame

The theme of #SquidGame is not new—we have seen such dystopian themes in films like The Hunger Games, Battle Royale, and 13 Tzameti.  But the compelling, diverse, and relatable characters—and the tenderness of their bond—will make you root for them.

"I am not a horse; I am a human." Amidst the brutality and violence, #SquidGame, at its core, is a social commentary on the ethical and moral ambiguity of human beings. It makes us question our existence. Who are we? What values do we stand for during our lowest points?  https://t.co/ioUUujSnlx

So I think this was just another sign of his selfless nature. He WANTS to see his daughter. But he NEEDS to save countless lives from suffering the way he suffered. He watched his friends die, he saw his childhood friend become a monster. Gi-Hun is a true hero. #SquidGame  https://t.co/VVg3RAtg4b

So Gi-Hun knows that while he wants to see his daughter and be a good father to her, she is safe and happy without him and he is needed elsewhere. He needs to stop the cycle of death and pain caused by the Squid Games. That is imminent, his daughter is not. (Cont.) #SquidGame

Important to also note that his daughter is not in danger at all. She’s actually in a very good situation with her mother and stepfather who seems like a genuinely good person, even willing to help his wife’s ex-husband help his mother in the hospital. (Cont.) #SquidGame

Many reasons, all of which are educated guesses. He’s a good person and knows that going to extreme lengths to win, like Sang-Woo does, will be a hollow victory. The blood he spills will haunt him whilst he lives freely with his money. (Cont.) #SquidGame

Despite knowing that his selfless actions could potentially end his life and prevent him from his original goal, money to better his life and the lives of his loved ones (mother, daughter), he does it anyway. Why is that? (Cont.) #SquidGame

Throughout the games, he is selfless and puts his own life at risk to protect others. Many examples but one would be choosing 001 as a partner when others were thinking of strategic allies to help win the game. (Cont.) #SquidGame
